## The Modified Brilliant Split

The Modified Brilliant Split is the most important technical concept for any 1.5ct cushion buyer — and the decision most likely to cause regret if ignored.

[![Cushion cut diamond engagement ring yellow gold solitaire on white background](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioSuperImposeBox/Rings/505021/505021_M1_CSH_DIM_wht_0100CT_W_Box3_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

Every cushion cut diamond — natural or lab — falls into one of two sub-types, defined by how the pavilion facets are arranged:

**Cushion Modified Brilliant.** The dominant sub-type in Blue Nile's inventory. Additional pavilion facets break the stone's light return into many small, uniform reflections — the "crushed ice" effect. GIA and IGI certification lists this sub-type as "Cushion Modified Brilliant."

At 7.5mm face-up (1.5ct), the crushed ice pattern is pronounced and clearly visible: the entire face-up surface sparkling with fine, dense, uniform light. Photogenic in every lighting condition, particularly under direct overhead light and in photography.

**Cushion Brilliant.** Fewer, larger pavilion facets create a pattern of distinct, broader flashes. GIA and IGI describe this sub-type as "Cushion Brilliant." At 7.5mm face-up, it shows larger individual flashes with visible fire — rainbow colour dispersion at facet boundaries.

More three-dimensional in character than the modified brilliant. Closer in visual nature to the [old mine cushion cut](/old-mine-cushion-cut-diamond) of the 19th century.

**Why 1.5ct is the first size where the split matters visibly.** At 1ct (6.5mm), most buyers cannot reliably distinguish modified brilliant from cushion brilliant without a direct side-by-side comparison. At 1.5ct (7.5mm), the crushed ice carpet and the distinct flash zones are clearly different aesthetic statements. A 1.5ct modified brilliant and a 1.5ct cushion brilliant placed side by side look like different stones to most viewers.

**How to confirm which sub-type you are buying.** Check the GIA or IGI grading report's "Shape and Cutting Style" field: it reads either "Cushion Modified Brilliant" or "Cushion Brilliant." Then watch Blue Nile's 360° HD video: the modified brilliant shows dense, continuous glitter with no distinct large flash zones; the cushion brilliant shows individual, larger flashes with visible dark intervals and colour at the facet edges. For the full technical breakdown at every carat weight, see the [lab grown cushion cut diamond guide](/lab-grown-cushion-cut-diamond).

